  "opinion": "As a self-employed electrician in Bari with a background that’s a mix of practical hands-on work and a bit of theoretical curiosity, I’ve noticed how science gets framed in ways that often feel disconnected from everyday life. The gender gap in science isn’t just about numbers—it’s about who gets to see themselves in the field. I’ve seen it firsthand in my community: women in engineering or tech often feel like they’re stepping into a space that doesn’t quite fit, even when they’re doing the same work as men. For me, this isn’t just a problem to be solved—it’s a problem to be reimagined. Should we address it? Absolutely. But not with the usual corporate-speak or top-down policies. Real change starts when we stop pretending that science is a solitary pursuit and start recognizing that it’s a social one. My dad, who has a PhD, taught me that science is about asking questions, not about fitting into boxes. So, how do we fix it? By making science feel relevant and accessible to everyone, starting with the basics. I’ve spent time in workshops teaching kids in my neighborhood—many of whom are girls—to build simple circuits. It’s not about making them engineers; it’s about showing them that science is something they can do with their hands, right now. The key is to let them see themselves in the process, not just as future scientists but as people who can contribute today. This isn’t about fixing a problem; it’s about redefining what science can be. And that, I believe, is the most important thing we can do.",
